=====================================================
PHASE 2: LINUX FILE SYSTEM DEEP DIVE
=====================================================

OVERVIEW
Linux uses a hierarchical file system starting from the root directory (/).

Everything begins from:

/

KEY DIRECTORIES

/        → Root of the entire file system
/bin     → Essential command binaries (ls, cp, mv, cat)
/sbin    → System administration binaries
/etc     → Configuration files
/home    → User home directories
/var     → Variable data (logs, cache, spool)
/usr     → User programs and applications
/tmp     → Temporary files
/lib     → Shared libraries
/opt     → Optional third-party software

IMPORTANT CONCEPTS

- Linux does NOT use drive letters like Windows.
- Everything branches from /
- Configuration files are mostly in /etc
- Logs are in /var/log
- User data is in /home

COMMANDS USED TO INSPECT FILE SYSTEM

ls -la /
ls -l /etc
ls -l /bin | head
du -sh /home/*
du -sh /var/*
df -h
stat /etc/passwd

WHY THIS MATTERS

Understanding the Linux file system is critical for:
- Troubleshooting
- Log analysis
- Security auditing
- System administration
